<FeaturePage
  tagline="Context Injection"
  title="Agents Skip Exploration"
  description="AI coding agents waste most of their turns orienting — reading READMEs, listing directories, mapping the codebase. ostk front-loads this context silently. The agent's first turn is already productive."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>

  <h2>The experiment</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://needle-bench.cc">needle-bench</a> tests AI coding agents on real bugs frozen in Docker containers. Each model gets shell access and one instruction: <em>find the needle</em>. The test suite passes or it doesn&rsquo;t.
  </p>
  <p>Every model runs in three arms:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Native</strong> &mdash; the model&rsquo;s own harness (Claude Code, Codex CLI, etc.) with the provider&rsquo;s API key. No ostk. This is how most developers run agents today.</li>
    <li><strong>Kernel (OpenRouter)</strong> &mdash; ostk kernel, routed through <a href="https://openrouter.ai">OpenRouter</a> for fair cross-vendor comparison. Same API, same routing for every model.</li>
    <li><strong>Kernel (optimized)</strong> &mdash; ostk kernel, using the provider&rsquo;s own API key directly. Best-case performance for each model.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Same bugs, same turn limits, same token budgets. The variable is what infrastructure sits between the model and the codebase.
  </p>

  <h2>The results</h2>
  <div class="data-table-wrap">
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th></th><th>Mean</th><th>Median</th><th>Models improved</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Native (no OS)</td><td class="num">34.9%</td><td class="num">15.6%</td><td class="num">&mdash;</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Kernel (with context)</td><td class="num">69.2%</td><td class="num">72.9%</td><td class="num">&mdash;</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Delta</strong></td><td class="num accent"><strong>+34.3pp</strong></td><td class="num accent"><strong>+37.5pp</strong></td><td class="num"><strong>23/26</strong></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>
    23 of 26 models improved with context injection. The median jump was +37.5 percentage points. The effect held across all 8 vendors tested.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it works</h2>
  <p>
    AI coding agents waste most of their turns on orientation. In the native arm, a typical agent spends 5&ndash;10 turns reading README files, listing directories, running tests, and mapping the codebase before it starts debugging. That&rsquo;s token budget spent on information that could have been provided upfront.
  </p>
  <p>Context injection front-loads this information. The agent&rsquo;s first turn already knows:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>What the project does (README summary)</li>
    <li>Where the relevant files are (file tree, filtered to likely areas)</li>
    <li>What&rsquo;s failing (test output, error messages)</li>
    <li>What was recently changed (git log, diff summary)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Fewer turns wasted on exploration means more turns available for the actual task.</p>

  <h2>Budget vs frontier</h2>
  <p>Context injection lets cheap models match expensive ones.</p>
  <div class="data-table-wrap">
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Comparison</th><th>Rate</th><th>Resolve</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Claude Opus 4 native</td><td class="num muted">$15/MTok</td><td class="num">90.6%</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Claude Haiku 4.5 + context</td><td class="num muted">$0.80/MTok</td><td class="num accent">90.6%</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Haiku on the kernel matches Opus running natively &mdash; at roughly <strong>1/19th the cost</strong>. The same pattern repeats across vendors:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GPT-4o + kernel</strong> (81.2%) beats <strong>GPT-4.1 native</strong> (50.0%)</li>
    <li><strong>Gemini Flash + kernel</strong> (65.6%) beats <strong>Gemini 2.5 Pro native</strong> (28.1%)</li>
    <li><strong>Devstral 24B + kernel</strong> (75.0%) beats <strong>GPT-4.1 native</strong> (50.0%) &mdash; an open 24B model outperforms a closed frontier model</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How ostk does it</h2>
  <p>
    Two commands. The OS handles the rest.
  </p>
  <div class="code-block">
    <pre><code>$ ostk init        # one-time project setup
$ ostk boot        # starts the OS, injects context

# What the agent sees (invisible, in system prompt):
# - Project: api-server (Node.js + Express)
# - Files: 47 files, 3,200 LOC
# - Tests: 2 failing (auth.test.js:42, auth.test.js:67)
# - Recent: modified auth/middleware.js 2 hours ago</code></pre>
  </div>
  <p>
    <code>ostk init</code> scans your project once and creates a <code>.ostk/</code> directory. <code>ostk boot</code> reads the current project state &mdash; file tree, test output, recent changes, error messages &mdash; and assembles it into the agent&rsquo;s system prompt. The agent doesn&rsquo;t know it received context. It just starts with better information.
  </p>
  <p>
    No special model configuration. No fine-tuning. No prompt engineering on your part. The same mechanism tested across needle-bench runs on your project with the same two commands.
  </p>

  <h2>Beyond debugging</h2>
  <p>needle-bench measures debugging, but the principle generalizes. Any task where an agent spends turns on orientation benefits from context injection:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Code review</strong> &mdash; agent knows the PR context, related files, and test coverage before reading the diff</li>
    <li><strong>Feature implementation</strong> &mdash; agent knows the architecture, existing patterns, and dependency constraints upfront</li>
    <li><strong>Refactoring</strong> &mdash; agent knows what depends on what before it starts moving code</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The mechanism is the same: reduce exploration turns, increase productive turns.</p>

  <h2>Constraints</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Context injection adds tokens to the system prompt. Overhead depends on project size.</li>
    <li>Injected context can be stale if the project state changed since the last boot.</li>
    <li>Works best when the task is related to files already in the project. Less effective for greenfield code with no existing structure to reference.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Try it</h2>
  <p>
    Install ostk, run <code>ostk init</code> in your project, then <code>ostk boot</code>. See the difference on your own codebase.
  </p>
